Introduction

Child mortality is among the most significant indicators of a countryâs healthcare, and development overall.

This report presents different techniques in data analytics for visualising global child mortality trends.

Specifically, we wish to answer a series of important questions:

  • Where are the global areas of very high child mortality?
  • How healthcare infrastructure is associated with child mortality?
  • Is there a relationship between GDP per capita and child mortality?

To show that child mortality inequalities require urgent attention globally, we provide maps, bar charts, scatterplots, line charts and pie charts.

1. Child Mortality Hotspots

Where are the global hotspots for child mortality?

In this visualization the number of child deaths in total per country is displayed as a choropleth.
Darker shades indicate higher child deaths. Countries such as Nigeria and India are dark in color,
signifying where the greatest need of interventions occurred.
Gray areas are missing data.

Code 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from mpl_toolkits.axes_grid1 import make_axes_locatable
import geopandas as gpd
import polars as pl
import pandas as pd
from plotnine import *
import ipywidgets as widgets
from IPython.display import display
import random


world = gpd.read_file("https://public.opendatasoft.com/api/explore/v2.1/catalog/datasets/world-administrative-boundaries/exports/shp")
tableau_data = pl.read_csv("/content/child_mortality_cleaned.csv")

df = (
    tableau_data
    .group_by("country_code")
    .agg(pl.col("child_deaths").sum().alias("total_deaths"))
    .to_pandas()
)

merged = world.merge(df, how="left", left_on="iso3", right_on="country_code")

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(15, 8))
divider = make_axes_locatable(ax)
cax = divider.append_axes("bottom", size="5%", pad=0.2)

plot = merged.plot(
    column="total_deaths",
    cmap="YlOrRd",
    linewidth=0.5,
    ax=ax,
    edgecolor="0.8",
    legend=False,
    missing_kwds={"color": "lightgrey", "label": "No data"}
)

sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap="YlOrRd", norm=plt.Normalize(vmin=merged["total_deaths"].min(), vmax=merged["total_deaths"].max()))
sm._A = []

cbar = fig.colorbar(sm, cax=cax, orientation="horizontal", shrink=1)
cbar.set_label("Total Child Deaths", fontsize=12)

ax.set_title("Child Mortality Hotspots: Total Child Deaths by Country", fontsize=16)
ax.axis("off")

plt.show()

2. Available Hospital Beds

This horizontal bar chart shows the top 10 countries sorted by average hospital beds per capita. Each countryâs value has a unique color, with the value shown within the bar. More hospital beds per capita increases health capacity, which suggests preparedness to deliver important care.

Code 
df = (
    tableau_data
    .filter(pl.col("hospital_beds").is_not_null())
    .group_by("country")
    .agg(pl.col("hospital_beds").mean().alias("avg_beds"))
    .sort("avg_beds", descending=True)
    .head(10)
    .to_pandas()
)

def generate_color_map(countries):
    color_map = {}
    used = set()
    for c in countries:
        while True:
            col = "#{:06x}".format(random.randint(0, 0xFFFFFF))
            if col not in used:
                used.add(col)
                color_map[c] = col
                break
    return color_map

color_map = generate_color_map(df["country"].tolist())

plot = (
        ggplot(df, aes(x='reorder(country, avg_beds)', y='avg_beds', fill='country')) +
        geom_col() +
        geom_text(
            aes(label='round(avg_beds, 1)'),
            ha='right',
            nudge_y=1,
            size=10
        ) +
        scale_fill_manual(values=color_map) +
        coord_flip() +
        labs(
            title=f"Top 10 Countries with Hospital Beds per Capita",
            x="Country", y="Average Beds per 10,000 People"
        ) +
        theme_minimal() +
        theme(figure_size=(9, 6))
    )


display(plot)

3. GDP Child Mortality Scatterplot

This scatterplot examines the relationship between GDP per capita and child mortality.
There is a clear negative association:
Higher GDP countries tend to have lower child deaths.
The bubble size reflects the size of their GDP, and the regression line shows a negative trend!

Code 
df = (
    tableau_data
    .filter((pl.col("child_deaths").is_not_null()) & (pl.col("gdp_per_capita").is_not_null()))
    .group_by("country")
    .agg([
        pl.col("child_deaths").mean().alias("avg_deaths"),
        pl.col("gdp_per_capita").mean().alias("avg_gdp")
    ])
    .sort("avg_deaths", descending=True)
    .head(10)
    .to_pandas()
)

def generate_color_map(countries):
    color_map = {}
    used_colors = set()
    for country in countries:
        while True:
            color = "#{:06x}".format(random.randint(0, 0xFFFFFF))
            if color not in used_colors:
                used_colors.add(color)
                color_map[country] = color
                break
    return color_map

color_map = generate_color_map(df["country"].tolist())

plot = (
    ggplot(df, aes(x='avg_gdp', y='avg_deaths')) +
    geom_point(aes(color='country', size='avg_gdp'), alpha=0.7, stroke=0.5) +
    geom_smooth(method='lm', color='#F47942', size=1.2, se=False, na_rm=True) +
    scale_color_manual(values=color_map) +
    scale_size_continuous(range=[5, 10]) +
    scale_x_continuous(labels=lambda l: [f"{int(val/1000)}K" for val in l]) +
    labs(
        title="How GDP Influences Child Mortality (Top 10 Countries)",
        subtitle="Top 10 countries by child mortality compared to GDP per capita.\nThe trend line shows general relationship across the selection.",
        x="GDP per Capita",
        y="Average Child Deaths",
        color="Country",
        size="GDP (Size)"
    ) +
    theme(
        figure_size=(12, 7),
        panel_background=element_blank(),
        plot_background=element_blank(),
        panel_grid_major=element_blank(),
        panel_grid_minor=element_blank(),
        axis_line=element_line(color='black'),
        axis_ticks_major=element_line(color='black'),
        legend_position='right',
        plot_title=element_text(size=16, weight='bold', margin={'b': 10}),
        axis_text=element_text(size=10),
        axis_title=element_text(size=12)
    )
)

display(plot)

4. Trends in Child Mortality Rates over Time

This line graph displays the total number of child deaths per year globally averaged between 1990 & 2022. Positive trend: As time has progressed, child mortality has decreased each year. This is a testament to the collective impact of global health activities, education, nutrition, and improved healthcare access.

Code 
df = (
    tableau_data
    .filter((pl.col("child_deaths").is_not_null()) & (pl.col("year").is_not_null()))
    .group_by("year")
    .agg(pl.col("child_deaths").mean().alias("avg_child_deaths"))
    .sort("year")
    .to_pandas()
)

plot = (
    ggplot(df, aes(x='year', y='avg_child_deaths')) +
    geom_line(color="#F47942", size=1.5) +
    geom_point(color="#F47942", size=2.5) +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks=list(range(df["year"].min(), df["year"].max() + 1, 2))) +
    scale_y_continuous(limits=(0, df["avg_child_deaths"].max() * 1.1)) +
    labs(
        title="Global Trend in Child Mortality Over Time",
        subtitle="This line chart illustrates the global average of child deaths from 1990 to 2022.",
        x="Year",
        y="Average Child Deaths"
    ) +
    theme(
        figure_size=(12, 6),
        panel_background=element_blank(),
        plot_background=element_blank(),
        panel_grid_major=element_line(color="#e0e0e0"),
        panel_grid_minor=element_blank(),
        axis_line=element_line(color='black'),
        axis_ticks=element_line(color='black'),
        text=element_text(size=12),
        plot_title=element_text(size=16, weight='bold', margin={'b': 10}),
        plot_subtitle=element_text(size=11, margin={'b': 10}),
        axis_title_x=element_text(margin={'t': 10}),
        axis_title_y=element_text(margin={'r': 10}),
        legend_position='none'
    )
)

display(plot)

5. Distribution of Child Mortality (Pie Chart)

This pie chart reflects the distribution of child deaths, over the most recent year, among the four worst performing countries. It illustrates how a small number of countries account for a very high proportion of global child deaths. Improving outcomes in a few very specific locations would make a substantial difference.

Code 
latest_year = tableau_data.select(pl.col("year").max()).item()

df = (
    tableau_data
    .filter((pl.col("year") == latest_year) & (pl.col("child_deaths").is_not_null()))
    .group_by("country")
    .agg(pl.col("child_deaths").mean().alias("avg_child_deaths"))
    .sort("avg_child_deaths", descending=True)
    .head(4)
    .to_pandas()
)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(7, 7))
colors = ['#FF9999', '#66B3FF', '#99FF99', '#FFD700']
ax.pie(
    df['avg_child_deaths'],
    labels=df['country'],
    autopct='%1.1f%%',
    startangle=140,
    colors=colors,
    textprops={'fontsize': 12}
)
ax.set_title(f"Share of Child Mortality by Country (Top 4) - {latest_year}", fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Conclusion

The visual data evidence above reveals the intricacy of child mortality globally.
We have identified major geographical disparities, relationships between economic strength and survival rates, and some of the evidence of the importance of health care and health care infrastructure. Fortunately, child mortality has consistently declined significantly over the past three decades.
That said, the evident concentration of mortality in a few countries will continue to require ongoing localized and strategic interventions to address ongoing risks and to reduce preventable child deaths. Sustained investments into health, infrastructure, and economic development will continue to be key.
